@Barry Ancona 

This STEVE had no idea about the Minecraft character, but I had --EVE and figured it probably was my namesake.  But it seemed too mundane to be the protagonist of a cool video game, so I held off.

And that's where I finally finished up.

@SP 

That's what I think as well.  Elegant and classy. 
The Ken more than made up for the Arhat...

@John H. 

This John H agrees!

Has trouble on the lower half but only a couple of minutes over my Friday average…

@Steve L 

Actually, he lives within walking distance. He doesn’t own a computer, nor a cell phone. The puzzles are submitted on graph paper. In ink.

Trust me. This explains so much, doesn’t it?

@Clem 

Not just ink. Fountain pen.

I know, because I tried to peek over his shoulder once, and he stabbed me with it.

@Greg Anderson 

Watch for PELE three times in the next two weeks. Sports people are like that: Bobby ORR and Mel OTT, for instance, often show up in spurts, then disappear again for months or years.

When I hear about these puzzles supposedly being a year in preparation, coming in from different people in diverse places, I just have to laugh. Pull the other one, NYT!

@Amanda 

That's amazing.  Together with yesterday's ARHAT, that makes three times you've encountered it in 48 hours!
Lol, maybe play the lottery?

@Andrew 
Nice to have some company.  I never read the LOTR and barely survived the movie (kept falling asleep); ditto GOT.  This means I'm helpless when Sauron appears.  "Fire and Ice" just means *Iceland* to me.   And Minecraft shall remain a mystery.

I play a lot of card games...but I held off on MELDS because it seemed unlikely...  BOOKS?  "Canastas" was too long, as was FULL HOUSE (but not FLUSH.)

@Steve L 
Siri is smarter than Alexa, who said, "Sorry, I don't know that one." All you Appleheads can gloat about that.
Also, the Fire table must have a thousand emojis but no skull.

@PuzzleDog 
Yep, it was WAVEDAT for me too for far too long. WAVEDHI just didn’t scan right for me, but I expect that’s a cultural/age thing.
If not sisters then mothers.  Eek

@PuzzleDog 

I was married to "spouse" at 54a for far too long. *groan* That made WAVED*P pretty puzzling.

I can't remember how/where I came across it recently (tried googling, halfheartedly), but it was a whole bit about NASA's joke in sending Juno (the probe) to check up on Jupiter, whose moons are named after the lovers and progeny of mythical Jupiter/Zeus's many, many alduterous affairs. The "angry wife" trope was difficult for me to shake today.

@Weak 
